From: Spack Project <spack@llnl.gov>
Subject: Fix __builtin_ia32_tpause for both GCC and Clang

The __builtin_ia32_tpause intrinsic has different signatures between GCC and Clang:

GCC (gcc/x86_64-linux-gnu/*/include/waitpkgintrin.h):
  __builtin_ia32_tpause(unsigned int control, unsigned long long counter)

LLVM/Clang (clang/lib/Headers/waitpkgintrin.h):
  __builtin_ia32_tpause(unsigned int control, unsigned int edx, unsigned int eax)

GCC accepts the 64-bit counter directly, while Clang requires it to be split
into EDX:EAX (high:low 32-bit parts) to match Intel's TPAUSE instruction encoding.

Clang's _tpause() wrapper in waitpkgintrin.h performs this splitting:
  _tpause(unsigned int __control, unsigned long long __counter)
  {
    return __builtin_ia32_tpause(__control,
      (unsigned int)(__counter >> 32), (unsigned int)__counter);
  }

But GCC's _tpause() wrapper passes the 64-bit value directly to its 2-arg builtin.

Onnxruntime PR #24524 (merged 2025-05-31, first in v1.23.0) bypassed the
_tpause() wrapper and called __builtin_ia32_tpause() directly with 2 arguments,
which works with GCC but fails with Clang:

  error: too few arguments to function call, expected 3, have 2
    __builtin_ia32_tpause(0x0, __rdtsc() + tpause_spin_delay_cycles);

This patch uses the portable _tpause() wrapper that works with both compilers,
as it's already included via <immintrin.h>. This makes the Linux code path
match the Windows code path.

References:
- https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/24524
- gcc x86_64-linux-gnu/14/include/waitpkgintrin.h (2-arg builtin)
- llvm-project/clang/lib/Headers/waitpkgintrin.h (3-arg builtin)
- Intel SDM Vol. 2B: TPAUSE instruction (EDX:EAX = 64-bit TSC value)

--- a/onnxruntime/core/common/spin_pause.cc
+++ b/onnxruntime/core/common/spin_pause.cc
@@ -35,7 +35,8 @@ void SpinPause() {
 #if defined(_WIN32)
     _tpause(0x0, __rdtsc() + tpause_spin_delay_cycles);
 #elif defined(__linux__)
-    __builtin_ia32_tpause(0x0, __rdtsc() + tpause_spin_delay_cycles);
+    // Use portable _tpause() wrapper that works with both GCC and Clang
+    _tpause(0x0, __rdtsc() + tpause_spin_delay_cycles);
 #else
     _mm_pause();
 #endif
